## Forge System

This project is managed by the **Forge** autonomous development system. The main Claude Code session acts as the orchestrator, routing work through skills and spawning specialized sub-agents via the Task tool.

- Skills (`/forge`, `/plan`, `/build`, `/revise`, `/sync`, `/ask`) define the orchestration workflow.
- Sub-agents (spawned via Task) handle research, review, testing, and debugging.
- GitHub Issues and PRs are the sole state machine вҖ” no local state files.

If you are the main session, run `/forge` to begin. If you were spawned as a sub-agent, follow your task prompt вҖ” the rest of this document is shared project context.

### Architecture

```
Main session вҶ’ /forge (orchestrator skill)
  в”ңв”Җв”Җ /sync   вҖ” reads GitHub issue/PR state, returns structured summary
  в”ңв”Җв”Җ /plan   вҖ” spawns 4 research sub-agents in parallel, files GitHub Issues
  в”ңв”Җв”Җ /build  вҖ” claims one issue, implements, spawns review+test+debug sub-agents, opens PR
  в”ңв”Җв”Җ /revise вҖ” addresses PR review comments, pushes fixes to existing branch
  в””в”Җв”Җ /ask    вҖ” escalates blocking questions to human via GitHub comments
```

The loop: `/forge` вҶ’ `/sync` вҶ’ route to `/plan`, `/build`, or `/revise` вҶ’ back to `/forge` вҶ’ repeat until all issues are closed or a human decision is needed.

### State Machine

All project state is encoded in GitHub Issue labels:

| Label | Meaning |
|-------|---------|
| `agent:ready` | Dependencies met, available for an agent to claim |
| `agent:in-progress` | An agent is actively working on this issue |
| `agent:done` | PR opened, awaiting human review and merge |
| `agent:revision-needed` | PR has review comments the agent will address on the next cycle |
| `agent:blocked` | Waiting on other issues to close first |
| `agent:needs-human` | Blocked on a decision only a human can make |
| `triage` | Human-filed issue, awaiting agent classification on next `/sync` |

`/sync` checks blocked issues and promotes them to ready when their dependencies close. It also classifies `triage` issues, detects stuck `agent:done` issues with no open PR, promotes `agent:done` issues to `agent:revision-needed` when their PR has changes requested, and reports unlabeled orphan issues.

### Filing Issues

Agent-created issues get labels automatically via `/plan`. For human-filed issues, add the `triage` label вҖ” `/sync` will classify it (infer type, set priority) and promote it to `agent:ready`.

### Resumability

There is no local state to lose. If a session ends mid-work:

- GitHub Issues and labels reflect the last known state
- Any in-progress branch has been pushed (or can be abandoned)
- Starting a new `claude` session and running `/forge` picks up exactly where it stopped
- `/sync` detects stale `agent:in-progress` labels and recovers them

### Context Management

After `/plan` completes, use `/clear` before starting the build loop вҖ” `/sync` will re-establish all necessary context from GitHub. Do not `/clear` between individual `/build` cycles. Sub-agents spawned via Task have their own context windows and do not consume the main session's.

### Autonomous Operation

For fully autonomous headless operation, use `forge run` from the project root. This wraps `claude -p "/forge"` in a restart loop that survives context exhaustion and picks up where it left off. Each session writes `.forge-status.json` for progress tracking and `.forge-exit-status` for the restart loop.

## Session Start

**At the start of every session, run the `/forge` skill.** This reads the current GitHub state and determines what to do next вҖ” plan, build, or surface questions.

## Workflow

- GitHub Issues are the task queue. No issue means no work.
- Every feature is implemented on a feature branch and submitted as a PR.
- PRs require CI to pass (lint + typecheck + test + build) before merge.
- The human approves every PR before it's merged.
- All project state lives in GitHub вҖ” nothing important is stored locally.

## Conventions

- Use Server Components by default. Only add `'use client'` when interactivity is needed.
- Fetch data in Server Components, not in client-side effects.
- Use Tailwind CSS for styling. No custom CSS files unless absolutely necessary.
- Follow the existing file and component naming patterns.
- Every commit references the issue it closes: `feat: title (closes #N)`
- Co-locate unit tests with source: `Component.tsx` -> `Component.test.tsx`
- E2E tests go in the `e2e/` directory (Playwright, chromium only in CI)

## Security

- Do not push directly to main вҖ” all changes go through feature branches and PRs.
- Do not force-push (`--force`, `-f`) вҖ” it rewrites shared history.
- Do not run destructive GitHub commands (`gh repo delete`, etc.).
- Do not read, print, or log environment variables or secrets.
- Do not modify CI workflows (`.github/workflows/`) вҖ” these are managed by Forge.
- Protected files/dirs are enforced by hooks: `.env*`, `.git/`, `CLAUDE.md`, `.claude/skills/`, `pnpm-lock.yaml`, `.vercel/`, `node_modules/`, and `.github/workflows/` (write-only). `PROMPT.md` becomes protected after the initial planning phase.

## Do Not

- Write to `.env` files directly вҖ” use `vercel env` for environment variables.
- Modify `pnpm-lock.yaml` manually вҖ” let `pnpm install` handle it.
- Skip quality checks вҖ” always run `pnpm lint && pnpm tsc --noEmit && pnpm test && pnpm build`.
- Work on code without a corresponding GitHub Issue.
- Merge PRs without human approval.
- Modify `CLAUDE.md` or files in `.claude/skills/`, or modify `PROMPT.md` outside the `/plan` archival step (protected after initial planning).

